The Menchet Festival has been attested since the {{ill|Old Kingdom of Egypt|de|Altes Reich (Ägypten)|12=draft}}, during the reign of {{ill|Nyuserre Ini|de|Niuserre|12=draft}}. It is directly related to the festival of {{ill|Day of the Sand Holes|de|Chenep-scha|12=draft}}.

== Background ==

=== Old Kingdom ===
The Menchet Festival took place on the third day after the New Moon, following the Chenep-scha Festival, and symbolized the "clothing of the Moon."

== Twelfth Dynasty ==
In honor of the deified {{ill|Senusret II|de|Sesostris II|12=draft}}, during the reign of {{ill|Senusret III|de|Sesostris III|12=draft}}, the festival was also referred to as "The Clothing of Senusret II." It was celebrated after the "Day of Fetching Sand for Anubis on His Mountain" in the Pyramid City of Senusret II, the Blessed One.

The {{ill|Pyramid of Senusret II|de|Sesostris-II.-Pyramide|12=draft}} at {{ill|El-Lahun|de|Al-Lahun|12=draft}} was traditionally associated with the "Mountain of {{ill|Anubis|de|Anubis|12=draft}}." In the papyri examined by {{ill|Ludwig Borchardt|de|Ludwig Borchardt|12=draft}}, festival dates are recorded for two different years:  
- 27th of Akhet II  
- 17th of Akhet II in the following year.

These have since been correlated to the 36th and 37th regnal years of {{ill|Amenemhat III|de|Amenemhet III|12=draft}}.

However, the similarly named month {{ill|Menchet (month)|de|Menchet (Monat)|12=draft}} had no direct connection to this festival. The month was named after the goddess {{ill|Menchet (Egyptian mythology)|de|Menchet (ägyptische Mythologie)|12=draft}}, who was responsible for clothing the gods on their birthdays.

